text.tspan: Any linearizable implementation of a strongly non-commutative method
has to contain either an AWAR or RAW primitive.
Is it possible to design an ordered data-structure without
strong synchronization in the insert method?
Can such a design provide good performance?
If timestamps are generated concurrently, then the inserts run concurrently.
Linearizability does not require an order on concurrent operations.
For linearizability only sequentially generated timestamps have to be ordered.
Without strong synchronization the same timestamp may be generated twice.

The order between concurrent remove operations depends on the

Elements are removed according to the virtual timestamp order, i.e. the

A queue implementation is linearizable wrt. queue semantics if
whenever two element are enqueued sequentially the younger element
is not removed before the older element.
The Timestamped Queue is linearizable wrt. queue semantics.
For queues a local correctness condition translates into global correctness.
For stacks recursive dependencies are possible.
No global linearization order is possible.
